Note: Dockerfile Translation Tests - Comprehensive test suite
Note: Part of Translation universal language translation system
Note: Tests lexer, parser, HIR translator and HIR-to-Dockerfile backend (which
Note: emits Dockerfile text directly via emitter_common — no separate printer
Note: step needed for the round-trip).

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/dockerfile/dockerfile_lexer.runa" as DockerfileLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/dockerfile/dockerfile_parser.runa" as DockerfileParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/dockerfile/dockerfile_to_hir.runa" as DockerfileToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/dockerfile/hir_to_dockerfile.runa" as HIRToDockerfile
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrimitive

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Local helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns a freshly allocated copy of s with leading and trailing ASCII
whitespace (space, tab, CR, LF) removed. The round-trip comparison trims
both the input source and the regenerated output before string_equals so
trailing-newline differences between the hand-written test sources and the
backend's canonical emission do not register as mismatches. Implemented
locally over core primitives (string_length, string_char_at,
string_substring) so the test stays self-contained and pulls in no
unrelated format module.
@End Reasoning
Process called "trim" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return s
    End If
    Let n be proc string_length from StringCore with s
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return s
    End If

    Let start be 0
    Let scanning be 1
    While scanning is equal to 1:
        If start is greater than or equal to n:
            Set scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let c be proc string_char_at from StringCore with s, start
            If c is equal to 32:
                Set start to start plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If c is equal to 9:
                    Set start to start plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    If c is equal to 13:
                        Set start to start plus 1
                    Otherwise:
                        If c is equal to 10:
                            Set start to start plus 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Set scanning to 0
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let endp be n
    Let scanning2 be 1
    While scanning2 is equal to 1:
        If endp is less than or equal to start:
            Set scanning2 to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let c2 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with s, endp minus 1
            If c2 is equal to 32:
                Set endp to endp minus 1
            Otherwise:
                If c2 is equal to 9:
                    Set endp to endp minus 1
                Otherwise:
                    If c2 is equal to 13:
                        Set endp to endp minus 1
                    Otherwise:
                        If c2 is equal to 10:
                            Set endp to endp minus 1
                        Otherwise:
                            Set scanning2 to 0
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let len be endp minus start
    Return proc string_substring from StringPrimitive with s, start, len
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Test Infrastructure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Captures a single test case outcome so the suite can aggregate pass/fail counts
and surface a precise failure message during summary reporting. error_message
is stored even on pass so that diagnostic flows can attach context without a
separate side table.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Plain triple holding the displayed test name, a 0/1 pass flag (Integer rather
than Boolean to match the Layout-encoded storage used by record_test_result),
and the failure detail string. Allocated as a 24-byte record by
record_test_result: name @0, passed @8, error_message @16.
@End Implementation
Type called "TestResult":
    test_name as String
    passed as Integer
    error_message as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
Holds the running totals for a Dockerfile round-trip test run. results is a
list pointer rather than an inline array so individual TestResult records can
be appended without reallocating the suite header, and the three counters are
kept independent of list length to allow O(1) summary printing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocated as a 32-byte record by create_test_suite with the following layout:
results pointer @0, total_tests @8, passed_tests @16, failed_tests @24.
record_test_result mutates the three counters in place via memory_set_int64
and appends to the list at offset 0.
@End Implementation
Type called "TestSuite":
    results as Integer  Note: Pointer to list of TestResult
    total_tests as Integer
    passed_tests as Integer
    failed_tests as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructs the TestSuite header that every other test routine mutates in
place. The list of TestResult records is created up front so subsequent
record_test_result appends never have to lazily initialise it, which keeps
that hot path branch-free.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates the 32-byte TestSuite header (results @0, total @8, passed @16,
failed @24), creates an empty List handle for the results slot, and zeroes
the three counters with explicit memory_set_int64 stores so the header is
fully initialised before any caller can read it.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_test_suite" returns Integer:
    Let suite_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 32

    Let results_list be proc list_create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 0, results_list
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 8, 0  Note: total_tests
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 16, 0  Note: passed_tests
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 24, 0  Note: failed_tests

    Return suite_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each test case routes through this single mutation point so that the
TestSuite invariant (total = passed + failed) is preserved by construction.
Storing the error_message on every record - including passes - lets the
summary printer attach diagnostics without a parallel branch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 24-byte TestResult (name @0, passed @8, error_message @16),
appends it to the results list at suite_ptr+0, then updates the appropriate
counter (passed_tests @16 or failed_tests @24) and unconditionally bumps
total_tests @8 via memory_get/set_int64 pairs.
@End Implementation
Process called "record_test_result" that takes suite_ptr as Integer, test_name as String, passed as Integer, error_message as String returns Integer:

    Let result_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with result_ptr, 0, test_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with result_ptr, 8, passed
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with result_ptr, 16, error_message

    Let results_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 0
    proc list_append from List with results_ptr, result_ptr

    Let total be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 8
    Set total to total plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 8, total

    If passed is equal to 1:
        Let passed_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 16
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 16, passed_count
    Otherwise:
        Let failed_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 24
        Set failed_count to failed_count plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 24, failed_count
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Renders the final pass/fail report from a fully-recorded TestSuite. Counts
are read directly from the header rather than re-derived from the list so
the summary stays O(suite_size) for the counter section and O(n) only for
the per-test loop. The failure detail line is conditionally emitted to
avoid noise on successful runs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads total/passed/failed from suite_ptr+8/+16/+24, then iterates the
results list at suite_ptr+0 by index using list_length+list_get. Each
TestResult is decoded by direct offset reads (name @0, passed @8,
error_message @16), and a [PASS]/[FAIL] line is emitted; the error
detail is only printed when passed != 1 and error_message is non-empty.
@End Implementation
Process called "print_test_summary" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 8
    Let passed be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 16
    Let failed be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 24

    Note: Print summary header
    Display "=================================="
    Display "Dockerfile Translation Test Summary"
    Display "=================================="
    Display ""

    Note: Print test counts
    Let total_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with total
    Display "Total tests: " joined with total_str

    Let passed_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with passed
    Display "Passed: " joined with passed_str

    Let failed_str be proc integer_to_string from StringPrimitive with failed
    Display "Failed: " joined with failed_str
    Display ""

    Note: Print individual test results
    Let results_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 0
    Let result_count be proc list_length from List with results_ptr

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than result_count:
        Let result be proc list_get from List with results_ptr, i
        Let test_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with result, 0
        Let test_passed be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with result, 8
        Let error_msg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with result, 16

        If test_passed is equal to 1:
            Display "[PASS] " joined with test_name
        Otherwise:
            Display "[FAIL] " joined with test_name
            If error_msg is not equal to "":
                Display "  Error: " joined with error_msg
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Display ""
    Display "=================================="

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Round-Trip Test Helper
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Every test_xxx case below funnels through this helper, which is the only
place that exercises the full Lex -> Parse -> HIR -> Backend -> Emit
pipeline end-to-end. Centralising round-trip validation here keeps the
per-instruction tests trivial (one source string + one call) and ensures
identical error-handling and normalisation policy across all 41 cases.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Drives five sequential stages. After each of the first four stages (lexer,
parser, HIR translator, HIR-to-Dockerfile backend) the routine reads the
component's has_error flag at the documented offset (lexer @32, parser
@32, translator @16, backend @16) and short-circuits with the captured
error string if set. Stage 5 trims both sides via string_trim and compares
with string_equals; on mismatch the recorded diagnostic contains both
Expected and Got so failures are debuggable without re-running the
pipeline. The backend now emits Dockerfile text directly, so no separate
print stage is required.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_round_trip" that takes suite_ptr as Integer, test_name as String, dockerfile_source as String returns Integer:

    Note: Step 1: Lex the source
    Let lexer_ptr be proc create_lexer from DockerfileLexer with dockerfile_source
    Let tokens_ptr be proc tokenize from DockerfileLexer with lexer_ptr

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer_ptr, 32
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Let error_msg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer_ptr, 24
        proc record_test_result with suite_ptr, test_name, 0, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2: Parse the tokens
    Let parser_ptr be proc create_parser from DockerfileParser with tokens_ptr
    Let dockerfile_ast_ptr be proc parse_dockerfile from DockerfileParser with parser_ptr

    Set has_error to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser_ptr, 32
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Set error_msg to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser_ptr, 24
        proc record_test_result with suite_ptr, test_name, 0, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 3: Translate to HIR
    Let translator_ptr be proc create_translator from DockerfileToHIR
    Let hir_block_ptr be proc translate_dockerfile from DockerfileToHIR with translator_ptr, dockerfile_ast_ptr

    Set has_error to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with translator_ptr, 16
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Set error_msg to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with translator_ptr, 8
        proc record_test_result with suite_ptr, test_name, 0, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 4: Translate HIR back to Dockerfile source text directly.
    Note: The backend now emits text directly via emitter_common — no intermediate
    Note: frontend AST construction and no separate printer step are required.
    Let backend_ptr be proc create_backend from HIRToDockerfile
    Let output_source be proc translate_hir_to_dockerfile from HIRToDockerfile with backend_ptr, hir_block_ptr

    Set has_error to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 16
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Set error_msg to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with backend_ptr, 8
        proc record_test_result with suite_ptr, test_name, 0, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 5: Compare output with input (normalize whitespace)
    Let input_normalized be proc trim with dockerfile_source
    Let output_normalized be proc trim with output_source

    Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with input_normalized, output_normalized

    If matches is equal to 1:
        proc record_test_result with suite_ptr, test_name, 1, ""
    Otherwise:
        Set error_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with "Output mismatch. Expected: ", input_normalized
        Set error_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with error_msg, " Got: "
        Set error_msg to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with error_msg, output_normalized
        proc record_test_result with suite_ptr, test_name, 0, error_msg
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Test Cases
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Anchors the FROM-instruction coverage at its simplest form (image plus
tag). The HIR backend must canonicalise this back to exactly one line
with no AS clause, no platform flag, and no digest, so this test is the
sentinel that detects accidental injection of those optional fields.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "FROM ubuntu:20.04\n" through test_round_trip under the label
"FROM basic". Pipeline failure surfaces via record_test_result.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_from_basic" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "FROM ubuntu:20.04\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "FROM basic", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates that the AS clause survives the round-trip. The HIR encodes the
stage name as a named field on the FROM node; this test catches regressions
where the backend drops or reorders that field.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "FROM ubuntu:20.04 AS builder\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_from_with_stage" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "FROM ubuntu:20.04 AS builder\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "FROM with stage", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pins the --platform flag placement. Round-tripping must keep the flag
before the image (Docker CLI requirement) rather than emit it as a
trailing option.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "FROM --platform=linux/amd64 ubuntu:20.04\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_from_with_platform" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "FROM --platform=linux/amd64 ubuntu:20.04\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "FROM with platform", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exercises the @sha256 digest form. The "@" separator and the algorithm
prefix must be preserved exactly; any tag-like rewrite would silently
change image identity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "FROM ubuntu@sha256:abc123\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_from_with_digest" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "FROM ubuntu@sha256:abc123\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "FROM with digest", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shell-form RUN is the unquoted variant that Docker forwards through
/bin/sh -c. The HIR distinguishes shell vs exec form by a boolean flag;
this test ensures the flag round-trips without the backend defaulting
to exec form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "RUN apt-get update\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_run_shell_form" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "RUN apt-get update\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "RUN shell form", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exec-form RUN is the JSON-array variant that Docker invokes via execve
without a shell. The argv elements must remain as separate quoted strings;
the test catches any collapse into a single shell string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "RUN [\"apt-get\", \"update\"]\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_run_exec_form" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "RUN [\"apt-get\", \"update\"]\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "RUN exec form", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMD in shell form sets the container's default command as a single
sh -c string. Mirrors RUN's shell/exec split; the test guards against
the backend coercing CMD into exec form when the parser saw shell form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "CMD python app.py\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_cmd_shell_form" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "CMD python app.py\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "CMD shell form", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
CMD in exec form is the production-preferred variant because it avoids
the sh wrapper and gives clean PID 1 signal handling. The test verifies
that the JSON-array argv stays an array.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "CMD [\"python\", \"app.py\"]\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_cmd_exec_form" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "CMD [\"python\", \"app.py\"]\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "CMD exec form", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Smallest LABEL case (one key=value pair). Confirms that the HIR stores
labels in a structure that preserves a single entry without wrapping it
into a multi-label aggregate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "LABEL version=1.0\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_label_single" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "LABEL version=1.0\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "LABEL single", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-pair LABEL exercises the parser's space-separated key=value list.
Order preservation matters because Docker's image inspect output relies
on declaration order; this test catches any reordering done by the
backend when materialising the label dictionary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "LABEL version=1.0 maintainer=user\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_label_multiple" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "LABEL version=1.0 maintainer=user\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "LABEL multiple", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
EXPOSE without an explicit protocol implies TCP. The test verifies that
the backend does not over-emit "/tcp" - the canonical form keeps the
default implicit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "EXPOSE 8080\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_expose_single_port" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "EXPOSE 8080\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "EXPOSE single port", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Uses /udp specifically because UDP is the non-default branch in the
HIR's protocol field; verifies the backend selects the correct protocol
string rather than silently substituting tcp.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "EXPOSE 8080/udp\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_expose_with_protocol" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "EXPOSE 8080/udp\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "EXPOSE with protocol", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multiple space-separated ports verify the HIR represents EXPOSE's port
list as an ordered collection rather than splitting into multiple EXPOSE
nodes, which would alter the printed form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "EXPOSE 8080 9090\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_expose_multiple_ports" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "EXPOSE 8080 9090\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "EXPOSE multiple ports", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Covers the equals-form ENV (the production-preferred form). The legacy
space-form is intentionally not tested here because the backend
canonicalises to equals-form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "ENV NODE_ENV=production\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_env_single" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "ENV NODE_ENV=production\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "ENV single", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two-variable ENV exercises the parser's pair list. The backend must
emit both pairs on a single ENV line (not split into two ENV nodes) to
match the source exactly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "ENV NODE_ENV=production PORT=8080\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_env_multiple" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "ENV NODE_ENV=production PORT=8080\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "ENV multiple", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Baseline COPY (source plus destination, no flags). Establishes that the
HIR's flag list defaults to empty rather than emitting "--from=" or
similar with placeholder values.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "COPY . /app\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_copy_basic" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "COPY . /app\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "COPY basic", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
--from is the multi-stage build pivot that pulls files from a previously
named stage. The test guarantees the stage name survives the round-trip
since losing it would break stage isolation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "COPY --from=builder /app /dest\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_copy_with_from" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "COPY --from=builder /app /dest\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "COPY with --from", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
--chown sets file ownership inside the image. The "user:group" form
contains a colon that is also a Dockerfile-significant separator
elsewhere; the test guards against the parser splitting on the wrong
colon and losing the group component.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "COPY --chown=user:group . /app\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_copy_with_chown" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "COPY --chown=user:group . /app\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "COPY with --chown", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
--chmod takes an octal mode that must be emitted verbatim. Numeric mode
strings are easy to accidentally re-format (leading zero loss, decimal
conversion); this test pins the octal-string form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "COPY --chmod=755 . /app\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_copy_with_chmod" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "COPY --chmod=755 . /app\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "COPY with --chmod", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
ADD is COPY's superset (also handles tarball extraction and URLs). The
test must remain distinct from COPY to prove the HIR encodes the
opcode discriminant; a backend bug that aliased ADD->COPY would silently
drop archive semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "ADD archive.tar.gz /app\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_add_basic" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "ADD archive.tar.gz /app\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "ADD basic", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shell-form ENTRYPOINT wraps the command in /bin/sh -c, which loses
proper signal forwarding. Distinct test exists so a regression that
silently switched the form (changing PID 1 semantics in production
images) gets caught.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "ENTRYPOINT python app.py\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_entrypoint_shell_form" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "ENTRYPOINT python app.py\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "ENTRYPOINT shell form", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exec-form ENTRYPOINT is the recommended form because the process runs
as PID 1 directly. Test pins this form distinctly from the shell-form
test so the form discriminant is verified in both directions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "ENTRYPOINT [\"python\", \"app.py\"]\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_entrypoint_exec_form" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "ENTRYPOINT [\"python\", \"app.py\"]\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "ENTRYPOINT exec form", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-path VOLUME is the shell-form variant (no JSON brackets). The
test ensures the backend selects the unquoted single-path emission
instead of always falling back to the JSON-array form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "VOLUME /data\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_volume_single" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "VOLUME /data\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "VOLUME single", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-path VOLUME requires the JSON-array form. The test verifies the
backend keeps the brackets, double-quoted paths, and comma separator
identical to the source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "VOLUME [\"/data\", \"/logs\"]\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_volume_multiple" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "VOLUME [\"/data\", \"/logs\"]\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "VOLUME multiple", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bare USER with no group establishes that the HIR's group slot can be
empty without forcing the backend to emit "appuser:" with a trailing
colon.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "USER appuser\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_user_basic" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "USER appuser\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "USER basic", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
USER with explicit group exercises the "name:name" form, distinguishing
it from the numeric "uid:gid" representation that Docker also accepts.
The test pins the name-form so it is not silently rewritten.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "USER appuser:appgroup\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_user_with_group" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "USER appuser:appgroup\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "USER with group", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
WORKDIR holds an absolute path token. Spotted-leading-slash failures
would break image working directory semantics; the test pins the
leading "/" preservation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "WORKDIR /app\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_workdir" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "WORKDIR /app\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "WORKDIR", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Defaultless ARG declares a build-time variable with no value. The HIR
must record the absence of a default explicitly so the backend does
not emit "ARG VERSION=" with a trailing "=".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "ARG VERSION\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_arg_basic" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "ARG VERSION\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "ARG basic", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARG with default exercises the "name=value" branch. The pair must
survive verbatim because Docker treats the default as the substitution
when no --build-arg is passed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "ARG VERSION=1.0\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_arg_with_default" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "ARG VERSION=1.0\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "ARG with default", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
STOPSIGNAL accepts either a numeric signal or a SIGxxx mnemonic. The
test uses the mnemonic form to verify the lexer keeps the SIG-prefixed
identifier as a single token rather than splitting on case boundaries.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "STOPSIGNAL SIGTERM\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_stopsignal" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "STOPSIGNAL SIGTERM\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "STOPSIGNAL", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HEALTHCHECK NONE is the cancellation form that disables inherited
healthchecks. The HIR must keep this as a distinct variant rather than
representing it as an empty CMD.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "HEALTHCHECK NONE\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_healthcheck_none" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "HEALTHCHECK NONE\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "HEALTHCHECK NONE", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HEALTHCHECK CMD in shell form embeds a URL containing "://" which can
confuse path-aware lexers. The test verifies the URL stays a single
token through the round-trip.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "HEALTHCHECK CMD curl http://localhost/\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_healthcheck_cmd_shell" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "HEALTHCHECK CMD curl http://localhost/\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "HEALTHCHECK CMD shell", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HEALTHCHECK CMD exec form puts the URL inside a JSON-array element.
The double-quote escaping plus the colon-in-URL combine to stress the
JSON tokeniser; this is the test that catches off-by-one quote bugs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "HEALTHCHECK CMD [\"curl\", \"http://localhost/\"]\n" via
test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_healthcheck_cmd_exec" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "HEALTHCHECK CMD [\"curl\", \"http://localhost/\"]\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "HEALTHCHECK CMD exec", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HEALTHCHECK with options exercises the option-list-before-CMD grammar.
Order of --interval and --timeout matters for diff-stability (the
backend must emit them in declaration order, not sorted).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits the full HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=10s CMD line via
test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_healthcheck_with_options" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=10s CMD curl http://localhost/\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "HEALTHCHECK with options", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
SHELL only accepts the JSON-array form (Docker grammar). The test
verifies the parser rejects the shell-form (no test for shell-form
exists by design) and the backend keeps the array intact.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "SHELL [\"/bin/bash\", \"-c\"]\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_shell" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "SHELL [\"/bin/bash\", \"-c\"]\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "SHELL", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
MAINTAINER is deprecated but still legal Dockerfile syntax. The
embedded "<...>" email brackets must not be interpreted as redirection
operators by any layer of the pipeline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Submits "MAINTAINER John Doe <john@example.com>\n" via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_maintainer" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "MAINTAINER John Doe <john@example.com>\n"
    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "MAINTAINER", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-stage build is the integration case that pairs an "AS builder"
FROM with a downstream "COPY --from=builder". This is the only test
that verifies cross-instruction references survive the HIR round-trip
intact.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Concatenates four Dockerfile lines (FROM AS builder, RUN, FROM alpine,
COPY --from=builder) and submits via test_round_trip.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_multi_stage_build" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "FROM ubuntu:20.04 AS builder\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "RUN apt-get update\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "FROM alpine:latest\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "COPY --from=builder /app /app\n"

    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "Multi-stage build", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The "everything together" integration test. Stacks nine different
instruction types (FROM, LABEL, ARG, ENV, WORKDIR, COPY, RUN, EXPOSE,
USER, CMD) in a realistic ordering so that any per-instruction
regression is amplified by interactions with surrounding instructions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a 9-line Dockerfile via successive string_concat calls and
submits via test_round_trip. Order matters: LABEL/ARG/ENV before
WORKDIR before COPY before RUN before EXPOSE/USER/CMD mirrors the
canonical production layering.
@End Implementation
Process called "test_complex_dockerfile" that takes suite_ptr as Integer returns Integer:

    Let dockerfile_source be "FROM ubuntu:20.04\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "LABEL version=1.0 maintainer=user\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "ARG VERSION=1.0\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "ENV NODE_ENV=production\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "WORKDIR /app\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "COPY . /app\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "RUN apt-get update\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "EXPOSE 8080\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "USER appuser\n"
    Set dockerfile_source to proc string_concat from StringPrimitive with dockerfile_source, "CMD [\"python\", \"app.py\"]\n"

    proc test_round_trip with suite_ptr, "Complex Dockerfile", dockerfile_source

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Test Runner
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entry point dispatched by the CI harness. The order of test invocation
mirrors the Dockerfile instruction grammar grouping (FROM first, then
RUN/CMD, then LABEL/EXPOSE/ENV, then file ops, then meta) so failures
correlate cleanly to grammar sections in the output log.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a fresh TestSuite, invokes all 41 test_xxx routines plus the
two integration tests, prints the summary, and returns 1 only if
failed_tests is exactly 0. The return value is the process exit
discriminant for the CI harness.
@End Implementation
Process called "run_all_tests" returns Integer:

    Let suite_ptr be proc create_test_suite

    Note: FROM instruction tests
    proc test_from_basic with suite_ptr
    proc test_from_with_stage with suite_ptr
    proc test_from_with_platform with suite_ptr
    proc test_from_with_digest with suite_ptr

    Note: RUN instruction tests
    proc test_run_shell_form with suite_ptr
    proc test_run_exec_form with suite_ptr

    Note: CMD instruction tests
    proc test_cmd_shell_form with suite_ptr
    proc test_cmd_exec_form with suite_ptr

    Note: LABEL instruction tests
    proc test_label_single with suite_ptr
    proc test_label_multiple with suite_ptr

    Note: EXPOSE instruction tests
    proc test_expose_single_port with suite_ptr
    proc test_expose_with_protocol with suite_ptr
    proc test_expose_multiple_ports with suite_ptr

    Note: ENV instruction tests
    proc test_env_single with suite_ptr
    proc test_env_multiple with suite_ptr

    Note: COPY instruction tests
    proc test_copy_basic with suite_ptr
    proc test_copy_with_from with suite_ptr
    proc test_copy_with_chown with suite_ptr
    proc test_copy_with_chmod with suite_ptr

    Note: ADD instruction tests
    proc test_add_basic with suite_ptr

    Note: ENTRYPOINT instruction tests
    proc test_entrypoint_shell_form with suite_ptr
    proc test_entrypoint_exec_form with suite_ptr

    Note: VOLUME instruction tests
    proc test_volume_single with suite_ptr
    proc test_volume_multiple with suite_ptr

    Note: USER instruction tests
    proc test_user_basic with suite_ptr
    proc test_user_with_group with suite_ptr

    Note: WORKDIR instruction tests
    proc test_workdir with suite_ptr

    Note: ARG instruction tests
    proc test_arg_basic with suite_ptr
    proc test_arg_with_default with suite_ptr

    Note: STOPSIGNAL instruction tests
    proc test_stopsignal with suite_ptr

    Note: HEALTHCHECK instruction tests
    proc test_healthcheck_none with suite_ptr
    proc test_healthcheck_cmd_shell with suite_ptr
    proc test_healthcheck_cmd_exec with suite_ptr
    proc test_healthcheck_with_options with suite_ptr

    Note: SHELL instruction tests
    proc test_shell with suite_ptr

    Note: MAINTAINER instruction tests
    proc test_maintainer with suite_ptr

    Note: Complex/integration tests
    proc test_multi_stage_build with suite_ptr
    proc test_complex_dockerfile with suite_ptr

    Note: Print summary
    proc print_test_summary with suite_ptr

    Let passed_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 16
    Let failed_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with suite_ptr, 24

    Note: Return 1 if all tests passed, 0 if any failed
    If failed_count is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    Otherwise:
        Return 0
    End If
End Process
